# CatNet AI Match Service

Small FastAPI microservice that powers the **AI Match** feature: upload a
photo of a cat, and CatNet finds visually similar Lost/Found posts.

## How it works

This is a **photo re-identification** system, not a classifier. There's no
labelled dataset of "these two photos are the same cat", so instead of
training a classifier from scratch we use **MobileNetV2** (pretrained on
ImageNet) as a fixed feature extractor:

1. Strip MobileNetV2's classification head, keep the convolutional base.
2. Run a cat photo through it, global-average-pool the output → a 1280-number
   vector ("embedding") that summarizes the photo's visual content (fur
   pattern, colors, shape, markings).
3. Two photos of the *same* cat produce embeddings that are close together
   (measured with cosine similarity). Photos of different cats end up
   farther apart.
4. No training step is required — this is the standard approach for
   visual-search / re-identification problems (same idea used by reverse
   image search and face-matching systems), and it's why this could be built
   in a day instead of weeks.

If you later collect a labelled dataset of confirmed cat-photo matches, you
could fine-tune the base model with triplet loss for better accuracy — the
rest of the system (storage, similarity search, API) wouldn't need to
change. That's a good "v2" if you want to keep improving this for your
resume/portfolio.

## Setup

```bash
cd ai-service
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate        # Windows: venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
uvicorn main:app --reload --port 8000
```

First run downloads the MobileNetV2 weights (~14MB) from
`storage.googleapis.com` — needs internet access once, then it's cached
locally by Keras.

Check it's alive: `curl http://localhost:8000/health` → `{"status":"ok"}`

## Endpoints

| Method | Path          | Body                              | Returns                     |
|--------|---------------|------------------------------------|------------------------------|
| GET    | `/health`     | –                                   | `{"status": "ok"}`          |
| POST   | `/embed`      | multipart file (`file`)            | `{"embedding": [1280 floats]}` |
| POST   | `/embed-url`  | JSON `{"url": "https://..."}`      | `{"embedding": [1280 floats]}` |
| POST   | `/similarity` | JSON `{"a": [...], "b": [...]}`    | `{"similarity": 0.0-1.0}`   |

The Node backend calls `/embed-url` right after a Lost/Found post's photo is
uploaded to Cloudinary (see `backend/services/aiMatch.service.js`), and calls
`/embed` when a user runs an AI Match search with a fresh photo they just
uploaded (that photo is never stored — only its embedding is used, in
memory, for that one request).

## Deploying alongside the backend

Set `AI_SERVICE_URL` in the backend's `.env` to wherever this service runs
(e.g. `http://localhost:8000` locally, or its deployed URL in production —
Render/Railway/Fly.io all work fine for a small FastAPI + TensorFlow-CPU
service like this).
